"Williams P.D., Guilyardi E., Madec G., Gualdi S., Scoccimarro E.","The role of mean ocean salinity in climate",2010,"Dynamics of Atmospheres and Oceans","49","2-3",,"108","123",,,10.1016/j.dynatmoce.2009.02.001,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75149139135&partnerID=40&md5=191b62322756a6713ee36aa27943088c","National Centre for Atmospheric Science, Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, United Kingdom; Laboratoire d'Oceanographie et de Climat: Experimentation et Approche Numerique (LOCEAN/IPSL), CNRS/Université Paris VI, France; Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia, Bologna, Italy","Williams, P.D., National Centre for Atmospheric Science, Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, United Kingdom; Guilyardi, E., National Centre for Atmospheric Science, Department of Meteorology, University of Reading, United Kingdom, Laboratoire d'Oceanographie et de Climat: Experimentation et Approche Numerique (LOCEAN/IPSL), CNRS/Université Paris VI, France; Madec, G., Laboratoire d'Oceanographie et de Climat: Experimentation et Approche Numerique (LOCEAN/IPSL), CNRS/Université Paris VI, France; Gualdi, S., Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia, Bologna, Italy; Scoccimarro, E., Istituto Nazionale di Geofisica e Vulcanologia, Bologna, Italy","We describe numerical simulations designed to elucidate the role of mean ocean salinity in climate. Using a coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation model, we study a 100-year sensitivity experiment in which the global-mean salinity is approximately doubled from its present observed value, by adding 35 psu everywhere in the ocean. The salinity increase produces a rapid global-mean sea-surface warming of 0.8 °C within a few years, caused by reduced vertical mixing associated with changes in cabbeling. The warming is followed by a gradual global-mean sea-surface cooling of 0.4 °C within a few decades, caused by an increase in the vertical (downward) component of the isopycnal diffusive heat flux. We find no evidence of impacts on the variability of the thermohaline circulation (THC) or El Niño/Southern Oscillation (ENSO). The mean strength of the Atlantic meridional overturning is reduced by 20% and the North Atlantic Deep Water penetrates less deeply. Nevertheless, our results dispute claims that higher salinities for the world ocean have profound consequences for the thermohaline circulation. In additional experiments with doubled atmospheric carbon dioxide, we find that the amplitude and spatial pattern of the global warming signal are modified in the hypersaline ocean. In particular, the equilibrated global-mean sea-surface temperature increase caused by doubling carbon dioxide is reduced by 10%. We infer the existence of a non-linear interaction between the climate responses to modified carbon dioxide and modified salinity. © 2009 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Climate; El Niño; ENSO; Global warming; Hypersaline; Ocean; Salinity; THC; Thermohaline circulation","Atmospheric carbon dioxide; Cabbeling; Coupled atmosphere ocean general circulation model; Diffusive heat; Hypersaline; Modified carbon; Nonlinear interactions; North Atlantic Deep Water; Numerical simulation; Ocean salinity; Sea surface temperatures; Spatial patterns; Surface cooling; Surface warming; Thermohaline circulations; Vertical mixing; World Ocean; Atmospheric chemistry; Carbon dioxide; Computer simulation; Experiments; Global warming; Nickel compounds; Salinity measurement; Oceanography; air-sea interaction; atmosphere-ocean coupling; climate forcing; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; general circulation model; global warming; hypersaline environment; numerical model; sea surface salinity; thermohaline circulation",,,,,,"Antonov, J.I., Levitus, S., Boyer, T.P., Steric sea level variations during 1957-1994 importance of salinity. (2002) J. Geophys. Res., 107 (C12), p. 8013; Bindoff, N.L., McDougall, T.J., Decadal changes along an Indian ocean section at 32 °S and their interp